Architectural interpretation (brief)

This priority order actually corresponds to three layers of work in your framework.

Execution layer

RepositoryRunner
RunnerPolicy
ProcessingStatus handling

→ Item 1

CLI framework layer

parseStandardCli
plugin option extensions
validation
help generation

→ Items 2–3

Plugin simplification

update-markdown-toc
nx-graph-to-mermaid
future plugins

→ Items 4–5

Important design consequence

Items 2 + 3 + 5 naturally converge to a single concept:

PluginDescriptor

Example concept:

export interface PluginDescriptor {
  name: string
  description: string

  options: CliOption[]

  validate?(config: StandardCliConfig): void
}

Which enables:

framework CLI
    ↓
parseStandardCli()
    ↓
pluginDescriptor.options
    ↓
validate()
    ↓
generateHelp()
    ↓
inject README help

So those three items form one coherent subsystem, not three independent tasks.

Execution order recommendation

Your order is already correct, but structurally it becomes:

1. Fix ProcessingStatus + Policy behavior
2. Extend CLI option validation
3. Move help printing into tooling-core
4. Simplify update-markdown-toc
5. Implement plugin help generation + README injection

This sequence avoids rewriting CLI logic twice.
